	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><placeName>The Hague</placeName>&#44; <date>24 Dec.57</date>.</p>
				<p>The Reverend</p>
				<p><addressee>I. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As soon as I did receive your kind letter &#40;date<lb/> <date>10 Nov.</date> last&#41; I inform myself by several persons<lb/> and especially by the Port. Charham here&#44; the <persName>Rev. Ferares</persName>&#44;<lb/> about the two Sepharim&#44; you are in need of.  All<lb/> informations concur in two points&#44; viz 1d there no<lb/> being copies of the S. F. to be had here this moment&#44;<lb/> and 2d. the ordinary price being higher than you<lb/> fixed it.  That price was ordinary to four hundred<lb/> guilders &#40;Neth. Money&#41;.  The <persName>Rev. Ferares</persName> has assu<lb/>red me&#44; if you could for that price per copy<lb/> and <add>&#63;</add> him a commercial house in this<lb/> country&#44; he would <sic>taken</sic> care of two copies<lb/> to be <sic>writed</sic> by an able sopher.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I hope you will agree in this&#44; in<lb/> every way you will be so kind to answer<lb/> me thereabout in time.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As for the <hi rend="underline">liste</hi> of Nr. publi&#45;<lb/>cations&#44; I am in the way to form that<lb/> for you&#44; and I will transmit it to you<lb/> very soon <hi rend="underline">via</hi> <placeName>London</placeName> with an exemplar<lb/> of the Nr. Yearbook for <date>1858</date>&#44; wherein<lb/> you will find&#44; I hope&#44; some interesting<lb/> papers&#44; viz a description of the <placeName>Chazaz</placeName><lb/> kingdom&#44; by <persName>Mr. Hartog</persName>&#44; a distinguished</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p><sic>scolar</sic> at <placeName>Leyden</placeName>&#59; an Episode of the<lb/> <sic>mediaval</sic> history of the Jew&#39;<sic>s</sic> in <placeName>Belgium</placeName>&#44;<lb/> by <persName>Mr. van Lier</persName>&#59; a Jewish novelle&#44;<lb/> by <persName>Mr. van Gigck</persName>&#44; a young lawyer here<lb/> and distinguished <sic>litterat</sic> also.  Those<lb/> three original productions may be interes&#45;<lb/>ting to be translated by <persName>Mr. Perez</persName>&#44; for<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Amongst the other works published<lb/> here in the last 25 or 30 years for the<lb/> special use of <add>&#63;</add>&#44; there will be<lb/> likewise some that will interest<lb/> you&#44; and I will venture to read<lb/> you as many as possible.  I will<lb/> put an advertisement in the only<lb/> Jewish paper we have to promote<lb/> your design.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Will agree&#44; sir&#44; my<lb/> thanks for the informations relating<lb/> to my family and will be so good<lb/> to continue me your correspondence.<lb/>  How the <persName>Ancona&#39;s</persName> doing now&#63;<lb/>  Their last tidings are from <date>May</date>&#44; I<lb/> believe.  I hope they are in good<lb/> health and they have not suffered<lb/> by the financial crisis that has visited<lb/> your shores&#44; like ours.</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Truly yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">J. J. Belinfante</persName></p>
		</body>
